m33a3yz5.reason:
tl/dr: This has swiftly become my favorite band over the past year or so, and this has become my favorite song. They are so incredibly talented, playing around constantly with key and time signatures, genres of music, and I’m a huge sucker for concept albums.
Starting off with the song, I love how epic it is. I know not everybody likes long songs, but Haken’s longest songs tend to be my favorites. I love how I can just get immersed in the music and the song can really develop and change over the course of the song. 
The song starts off feeling almost cinematic to me. They present the theme and the lyrics and music throughout really fit that theme of déjà vu, dreams, and questioning reality. Lines like “Dreams are real as long as they last, can we say more of life?” are lines that I love. It’s a topic I just find interesting on its own, and not commonly addressed in music. The song has a story as well which I really like. It was actually inspired by one of the band members who dreamt of their own death when they were a kid. I love how it ends kind of vague so you wonder if everything was in a dream, or if they’re insane. They bring all the parts of the song back together into a true climax towards the end of the song. This last chorus is my favorite. The ending where they start focusing a lot more on the violin, viola, and cello are incredible, and a very fitting way to end the song. Throughout the song I go from feeling a sense of mystery, curiosity to triumph, to horror, to confusion. All of this combines to an incredible experience.
The way the music is layered is also something I love. They introduce different things and then bring them back at later points, such as the keyboard triplets that always tickles my brain. The drum fills and the main guitar riff are awesome. Ross’s vocals have an almost ethereal nature which really fits as juxtaposition with some of the other instruments, and fits the theme really well. The guitar solo about halfway through is so beautiful, I feel that they don’t try too much to impress you as much as just make it a beautiful part of the song. 
While Haken is a Progressive Metal band, they wear their other influences on their sleeve at times. You may have noticed if you listened to the entire song that they had a cello, violin, viola, and French horn in the song. There was a section that was heavily inspired by Jazz, another that was inspired by Latin music, and another inspired by Middle Eastern music. I enjoy that they are constantly pulling from different places for inspiration.
Now, for more about the band. I had a friend recommend this band a few years ago and I tried listening to it but it bounced off of me several times until last July. They released their new album and a particular song, Sempiternal Beings, really caught my attention. Since then, each time I listen to their music I like it more and that continues to be true. I even went to go see them live back in February and I’m not much of a concertgoer.
Beyond Visions, many of their other songs would be extremely high in my list of favorite songs of all time. Pretty much their entire discography is incredible. They have a knack for writing great concept albums, which I mentioned I am a sucker for. In their most recent album, Fauna, each song is about a different animal (in a way). Sempiternal Beings is just about the jellyfish, but Elephants Never Forget is about the Elephant Man, Joseph Merrick.
When Oppenheimer came out Ryan mentioned that he really liked the metric modulation in the music from the movie. I mentioned that I really enjoy band that do that and I think he thought I was being sarcastic but I wasn’t. I don’t think Visions is the very best showcase of that aspect of the band, but it’s definitely still there. It’s one of the things I enjoy paying attention to while listening. Their songs often transition between 4/4, 5/4, 7/8, 11/8, 12/8, etc. Haken enjoys playing with different key signatures also. Sometimes they do this in a way that escapes notice unless you’re really paying attention.
The combination of incredible talent, creativity in the music writing and the content of their songs I think this band is just incredible. If you’ve enjoyed this journey and are interested in more, I can’t recommend their other music enough. Songs like Crystallized, Elephants Never Forget, and Cockroach King, and more are songs I strongly recommend. Their albums Affinity and the Mountain are perhaps their most accessible, but honestly their entire discography is incredible.
m33a3yz5.title: Visions

m33fsifk.reason:
Linkin Park may be my favorite band. I was very sad when Chester Bennington died, and I just expected that there would never be any new music. When I heard that the band was adding a new lead singer, I was skeptical that I would like the new stuff. This song immediately put that concern to rest. Emily Armstrong brings a different sound, but I love it. I can't stop listening to this song. 

About 80% of my love of this song is simply based on the music. I love the sound. And while I don't feel like the message is one I personally relate to, that of being stuck in a cycle of meaningless work with no reward, there are some lines that really hit for me. Especially these lines in the chorus:

[I] Let you cut me open just to watch me bleed
Gave up who I am for who you wanted me to be
Don't know why I'm hopin' for what I won't receive

I tried for a while to figure out how to express what I am about to say, and I'm not confident that I got it right. This is just one of those songs that allows me to feel my feelings. It isn't that the words reflect my inner feelings, but I'm able to get things out when I listen to this song.
m33fsifk.title: The Emptiness Machine

m33kjsdm.reason: Although I haven’t always loved and appreciated the Beatles as much as Gary, we watched the Beatles documentary and I fell In love with their music and history. This song recently came out and it was so cool to learn that this was a song that John started to record the piano demo for but never finished. And because of new technology they were able to piece together vocals of all the members and finish the song. This is considered the Beatles' final song. It was recorded 42 years after Lennon's death, 22 years after George's death, and 52 years after their last studio recording.
m33kjsdm.title: Now And Then

m34tjcrb.reason:
The original version of this song is actually in Italian and was released in 1982. It has been sung by various singers and I chose this version because it's the version I heard while watching the TV show, Berlin, with Vir.

It's a simple song about happiness (felicità). I like the melody and the lyrics. I fell in love with it in part because of the emotion in the show where it appears and in part because of the great memory with Vir and love that I feel for her.

In this version of the song, they say "felicità" in Italian, but the rest of the lyrics are Spanish and sung with an accent from Spain. This language combination is also significant to me because Vir and I chose to play a song for our wedding where Andrea Bocelli sang in Italian and we went to Italy together for our honeymoon. Vir has a lot of Italian ancestors and obviously we speak a lot of Spanish with each other.
m34tjcrb.title: Felicidad
